<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-837-064  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 837 064.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Sept 10 1990 v7 n36 p39(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Abacus, DME tools help Windows 3.0 handle files better. (AbacusInc.'s BeckerTools and DME Systems Specialities' Qdisk 5.0 filemanagement software)(Microsoft Windows 3.0 graphical userinterface) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Sullivan, Kristina B.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Abacus Inc. (product introduction)DME System Specialities (product introduction).andO;Product:   BeckerTools (File management software) (product introduction)Qdisk 5.0 (File management software) (product introduction)Microsoft Windows 3.0 (Graphical user interface) (computerprograms).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionFile ManagementSoftware packages.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Kristina B. SullivanandM;Windows 3.0 users who find the program's file-management utility lacking nowhave two new options from Abacus and DME Systems Specialties.andM;Abacus last month released BeckerTools for Windows 3.0, which provides morethan 200 file- and data-management functions, said officials at the GrandRapids, Mich., company.andP;  The program provides an &quot;undelete&quot; function notfound in the Windows 3.0 File Manager.andP;  It lets users copy, move, compare,delete and verify files with a single command.andM;The program also allows users to display and change file attributes; searchand replace text across multiple files; and show directories in a tree orlist format.andP;  BeckerTools also allows disk formatting, hard-disk backup tofloppies and printing files in hexadecimal or ASCII format.andM;Priced at $79.95, BeckerTools requires Windows 3.0.andP;  An AT-compatiblecomputer with 640K bytes of RAM is recommended.andM;DME's Qdisk version 5.0 gives Windows 3.0 users the ability to manipulatefiles from within any text-based application running under Windows.andP;  Userscan copy, move, delete and rename files, said David Ehrlich, president of thefirm.andM;With Qdisk 5.0, users can also reorganize directories and theirsubdirectories, Ehrlich said.andP;  Qdisk can also be used in a networkenvironment to move these directory tree structures from local hard disks toservers or among different servers, he added.andM;Qdisk can be run as a terminate-and-stay-resident application that requiresonly 4K bytes of RAM.andP;  In addition to Windows 3.0, the program runs underQuarterdeck Office Systems' Desqview and Novell NetWare 386, Ehrlich said.andM;Qdisk costs $39.95 and requires a PC running DOS 2.1 or higher with 256Kbytes of RAM.andP;  Current users can upgrade for $10.andM;DME System Specialities, of Laguna Hills, Calif., can be reached at (714)643-9767.andP;  Abacus can be reached at (800) 451-4319.andO;</TEXT></DOC>